I developed more knowledge of calc 2.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: Material is challenging
Weaknesses: Material is taught too fast
It could be improved by allowing for more partial credit and having more practice in class.

In terms of strength, the course had a lot of ways to seek extra help such as office hours and peer tutoring. This made the weekly p-sets very manageable. The fact that we could have a cheat sheet also made the midterms/final a lot less intimidating. In terms of weaknesses, the class was a little fast paced at times.

I liked how the course was taught where there was a lot of practice problems because that was very helpful when I had to review/study for the midterms/finals. I think a weakness may be how the homework problems can sometimes be a lot harder compared to what the class covered, so maybe going over more challenging problems in class will be helpful.
It is a challenging and fun course, rewarding if you are willing to work hard and take advantage of things like Office Hours.

The biggest weakness of this course is how rushed content becomes at the end. I found myself and my peers under lots of pressure in the last few weeks to learn what felt like a greater amount of content than we usually covered in 2-3 weeks. The strength of this course comes mainly from the instructor I had.
This course was well taught, but at times I felt the pace was a bit slow.
Claxx material was very engaging but oftentimes the problem sets felt like busy work instead too measures of knowledge and familiarity with the material.

Exams were way to hard and felt like the professors did not even try to prepare us in any way for them. The content felt very distant from the units we learned in class. Also, classes felt more dependent than ever on the professor, and I didn't hear of a single good professor.
Recordings of lectures

I thought this course provided me a solid understanding of Calc 2 but much of that came with my own practice. The lectures were fine but I often came out confused and ended up teaching myself the content. I also find that the grading system is unfair. So much time is spent on PSETs for them to count so minimally and the first midterm should be able to have more weight than the second.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes and no. It was challenging but also hard because a lot of students taking this class have already taken it in high school, so the students who haven't are in somewhat of a disadvantage.
I would not because I do not feel the tests allowed enough extra credit so missing one problem meant a bad grade.
If they need the distributional requirement, then yes. If it's not needed, I wouldn't recommend. The course can move fairly quickly and the weekly p-sets require high engagement with the material.
Yes! I think it's a good started class!
Yes! I think everyone should know some calculus, and this is a good way to learn it.
Only if you need to
Yes but it is a large lecture class, I felt that grading was not super transparent and I was unsure of my final grade until the end.
Yes! The classes were fun and engaging.
Unless needed for your major, no
If you required a math credit, great course to take
I would recommend this course to another student only if it is needed for their major.
